### Build-a-Bank · Step 26 · Hexagonal architecture — the API is UNCHANGED (that's the point)
### A behaviour-preserving structural restructure is invisible from outside: same endpoints, same JSON shape,
### same live SSE push as Steps 20/25 — now produced by the hexagon's ports-and-adapters wiring:
### Kafka → TransferEventConsumer (driving adapter) → NotifyOnTransfer port → NotificationService (use case)
### → ProcessedEventStore port → NotificationPublisher port → SseHub (driven adapter) → browser.
### Use these requests to verify that invisibility with your own eyes.
###
### The tell-tale: the dedupe log line is now signed by c.b.n.application.NotificationService
### instead of c.b.notification.TransferEventConsumer — same log level, same message, new owner.
###
### Start the pieces (4 terminals) — identical to Steps 20/25:
### 0) Broker (Redpanda, Kafka-API):
###    docker run -d --name bank-redpanda -p 9092:9092 redpandadata/redpanda:v24.2.7 \
###        redpanda start --mode dev-container --kafka-addr PLAINTEXT://0.0.0.0:9092 \
###        --advertise-kafka-addr PLAINTEXT://localhost:9092
### 1) Auth:           ./mvnw -pl services/auth spring-boot:run                                   # 8083
### 2) Postgres:       docker compose -f services/demand-account/compose.yaml up -d               # 5433
### 3) demand-account: SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5433/demand_account \
###                    AUTH_JWKS_URI=http://localhost:8083/oauth2/jwks \
###                    KAFKA_BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS=localhost:9092 \
###                    ./mvnw -pl services/demand-account spring-boot:run                         # 8082
### 4) notification:   KAFKA_BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS=localhost:9092 \
###                    ./mvnw -pl services/notification spring-boot:run                           # 8084

@auth = http://localhost:8083
@da   = http://localhost:8082
@note = http://localhost:8084

### A) The recent-notifications buffer (newest first) — same endpoint, same JSON shape as Steps 20/25.
### Empty [] until an event flows; after request E you'll see "Transfer of … completed."
### (produced by domain/Notification.from via the application use case through the NotificationPublisher port).
GET {{note}}/api/notifications

### B) Open a live SSE stream and LEAVE IT RUNNING — watch the hexagon deliver events in real time.
###    Terminal equivalent:  curl -N http://localhost:8084/api/notifications/stream
GET {{note}}/api/notifications/stream
Accept: text/event-stream

### C) Log in for a token (paste the JWT below).
POST {{auth}}/api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{"username":"alice","password":"password"}

@token = PASTE_JWT_HERE

### D) Open two accounts (the flow seeds its own data — no separate seed file needed).
POST {{da}}/api/accounts
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
Content-Type: application/json

{"accountNumber":"ACC-A","currency":"USD","openingBalance":200.00}

###
POST {{da}}/api/accounts
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
Content-Type: application/json

{"accountNumber":"ACC-B","currency":"USD","openingBalance":0.00}

### E) Transfer → Outbox row → relay → Kafka → TransferEventConsumer (driving adapter)
###     → notifyOnTransfer.handle(event) [inbound port] → NotificationService.handle
###     → processedEvents.markIfNew [outbound port] → publisher.publish [outbound port]
###     → SseHub.publish [driven adapter] → your SSE stream (request B) within ~2s.
### Same observable flow as Steps 20/25 — dependency arrows just point inward now.
POST {{da}}/api/v1/transfers
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
Content-Type: application/json

{"from":"ACC-A","to":"ACC-B","amount":40.00,"description":"rent"}

### 🧪 Experiment 1 (spot the new log owner): in notification's console, find:
###   c.b.n.application.NotificationService : notified: Transfer of 40.0 from ACC-A to ACC-B completed.
###   NOT: c.b.notification.TransferEventConsumer : notified: …   ← that was Steps 20/25
###   Same policy, new address — the restructure made it visible in ops output.

### 🧪 Experiment 2 (prove domain purity): in another terminal:
###   grep -h "^import" services/notification/src/main/java/com/buildabank/notification/domain/*.java | sort -u
###   → import java.math.BigDecimal;    (the whole domain's import surface — one line)

### 🧪 Experiment 3 (bytecode proof of the dependency rule):
###   ./mvnw -pl services/notification -DskipTests compile
###   javap -c -p services/notification/target/classes/com/buildabank/notification/application/NotificationService.class \
###     | grep -c adapter
###   → 0   (the use case's bytecode contains zero adapter references)

### 🧪 Experiment 4 (restart amnesia — the documented in-memory trade-off): restart notification,
### replay request E with a NEW transfer, check request A: the in-memory adapter forgot everything.
### The port is exactly where a Redis adapter would plug in (the durable-store stretch goal in the lesson).
